1.1 Import and prepare data¶

In [2]:
df = pd.read_csv(
    'dataset_mansion.csv', 
    sep=",")

# Replace the comma with dot in Consumption column and convert it to floating-point number format
df['Consumption'] = df['Consumption'].str.replace(',', '.').astype(float)

# Convert mtime column to datetime format
df['Time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['MTime'], format='%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')

# Drop unnecessary columns
df = df.drop(columns=['Unnamed: 0', 'MTime'])

# Set Time column as the index
df.set_index('Time', inplace=True)

# Calculate the moving average of temperature with window size of 6 datapoints/hours (option, might not needed in the final solution)
df['MovingAverageTemp'] = df['AirTemperature(degC)'].rolling(window=6).mean()

1.3 Box plots¶


















In [22]:






# List of columns to plot (without locations)
columns = [
    'Consumption', 'AirTemperature(degC)', 'HighestTemperature(degC)',
    'LowestTemperature(degC)', 'RelativeHumidity(%)', 'WindSpeed(m/s)', 'MaximumWindSpeed(m/s)',
    'MinimumWindSpeed(m/s)', 'WindDirection(deg)', 'PrecipitationAmount(mm)',
    'MaximumPrecipitationIntensity(mm/h)', 'AirPressure(hPa)', 'PresentWeather(rank)'
]

# Calculate the number of rows needed
num_columns = len(columns)
num_plots_per_row = 3
num_rows = (num_columns + num_plots_per_row - 1) // num_plots_per_row

# Create subplots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=num_rows, ncols=num_plots_per_row, figsize=(18, 6 * num_rows))

# Flatten the axes array for easy iteration
axes = axes.flatten()

# Plot boxplots for each column in the DataFrame
for i, column in enumerate(columns):
    df.boxplot(column=column, ax=axes[i])
    axes[i].set_title(f'Boxplot for {column}')

# Remove any unused subplots
for j in range(i + 1, len(axes)):
    fig.delaxes(axes[j])

# Adjust layout and display the plots
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Calculate the number of NaN values in the specified columns
nan_temp = df['AirTemperature(degC)'].isna().sum()
nan_consumption = df['Consumption'].isna().sum()

print(f'Number of NaN values in Consumption: {nan_consumption}')
print(f'Number of NaN values in AirTemperature(degC) - before cleaning: {nan_temp}')

# Replace NaN values in the AirTemperature(degC) column
df['AirTemperature(degC)'] = df['AirTemperature(degC)'].interpolate(method='linear')

nan_temp = df['AirTemperature(degC)'].isna().sum()
nan_consumption = df['Consumption'].isna().sum()

print(f'Number of NaN values in AirTemperature(degC) - after cleaning: {nan_temp}')

1.6 Times series - Consumption vs. temperature¶


















In [25]:






# Plot yearly consumption and temperature

# Get the list of unique years
years = df.index.year.unique()

# Plot each year in the separate graph
for year in years:
    df_year = df[df.index.year == year]
    fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5))

    # Plot Consumption on the primary y-axis
    ax1.plot(df_year.index, df_year['Consumption'], linestyle='-', linewidth=0.2, color='b')
    ax1.set_title(f'Consumption and Moving Average Temperature for {year}')
    ax1.set_xlabel('Time')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Consumption [kW]', color='b')
    ax1.set_ylim(0, 11)  # Set y-axis range
    ax1.grid(True)

    # Create secondary y-axis for MovingAverageTemp
    ax2 = ax1.twinx()
    ax2.plot(df_year.index, df_year['MovingAverageTemp'], linestyle='-', linewidth=0.2, color='r')
    ax2.set_ylabel('MA Temperature [degC]', color='r')

    fig.tight_layout()  # Adjust layout to prevent overlap
    plt.show()

1.7 Time series - Monthly and yearly overviews¶


















In [28]:






# Plot yearly data to the same graph (monthly)

# Resample to monthly consumption
monthly_consumption = df['Consumption'].resample('M').sum()

# Prepare the data for plotting
years = int(np.round(len(monthly_consumption) / 12))
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))
plt.grid(which='both')

# Plot each year's data
for i in range(years):
    index = monthly_consumption.index[i*12:(i+1)*12]
    month_names = ['January', 'February', 'March', 'April', 'May', 'June', 'July', 'August', 'September', 'October', 'November', 'December']
    plt.plot(month_names, monthly_consumption.loc[index].values, marker='o')
    plt.text(y=monthly_consumption.loc[index].values[-1], x=11, s=monthly_consumption.index[i*12].year, fontsize=12)

# Adding legend and title
plt.legend(monthly_consumption.index.year.unique(), loc='upper left')
plt.title('Monthly Energy Consumption per Year')
plt.xlabel('Month')
plt.ylabel('Energy Consumption [kWh]')
plt.show()












































In [29]:






# Plot yearly data to the same graph (weekly)

# Resample to weekly consumption
weekly_consumption = df['Consumption'].resample('W').sum()

# Prepare the data for plotting
years = int(len(weekly_consumption) / 52)
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))
plt.grid(which='both')

# Plot each year's data
for i in range(years):
    index = weekly_consumption.index[i*52:(i+1)*52]
    week_numbers = [f'Week {i+1}' for i in range(52)]
    plt.plot(week_numbers, weekly_consumption.loc[index].values, marker='o')
    plt.text(y=weekly_consumption.loc[index].values[-1], x=51, s=weekly_consumption.index[i*52].year, fontsize=12)

# Modify X-axis labels to show every 4th week
plt.xticks(ticks=range(0, 52, 4), labels=[f'Week {i}' for i in range(1, 53, 4)])

# Adding legend and title
plt.legend(weekly_consumption.index.year.unique(), loc='upper left')
plt.title('Weekly Energy Consumption per Year')
plt.xlabel('Week')
plt.ylabel('Energy Consumption [kWh]')
plt.show()
















































1.8 Hourly overview¶


















In [30]:






# Plot hourly data to the same graph (daily)

# Filter DataFrame for a specific month (e.g., July 2018)
df_month = df[(df.index.year == 2018) & (df.index.month == 2)]

# Get unique days in the month
days = df_month.index.day.unique()

# Plot each day in the specified month on the same figure
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
plt.grid(which='both')

for day in days:
    df_day = df_month[df_month.index.day == day]
    plt.plot(df_day.index.hour, df_day['Consumption'], marker='o', label=f'2018-02-{day:02d}')

# Adding title, labels, and legend
plt.title('Hourly Energy Consumption for January 2018')
plt.xlabel('Hour of the Day')
plt.ylabel('Energy Consumption [kWh]')
plt.xticks(range(0, 24))  # Set x-axis to show each hour
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()

# Correlation analysis
